column2: [('there is no evidence of acute hemorrhage, large acute territorial infarction, or overt mass effect. there is no shift of midline structures. ventricles and sulci are normal in size and configuration. there is no evidence of fracture. there is deviation of the nasal septum to the right, (2:3). there is incidental finding of likely osteoma in the right frontal sinus (2:12), measuring 1.4 x 1.1 cm.', 1, 0.0), ('there are small bilateral simple fluid attenuation subdural collections, representing hygromas or chronic subdural hematomas. there is no shift of midline structures. the ventricles, cisterns, maintain a normal configuration, except for a large 4-cm cystic structure in the right infratentorial space that likely represents an arachnoid cyst. periventricular white matter hypodensities are the sequelae of chronic small vessel infarction, and a lacunar infarct is present in the left external capsule. the osseous structures are unremarkable. there is atherosclerotic calcification of the cavernous carotids. there is partial opacification of the ethmoid sinuses and right sphenoid sinus.', -2, 0.0), ('from t11 to s4 level, there are no bony abnormalities indicative of metastatic disease. no evidence of epidural mass identified or thecal sac compression seen. mild degenerative disc disease is seen from t11-12 to l5-s1 level with minimal bulging. there is no spinal stenosis or high-grade foraminal narrowing. incidental perineural cysts are visualized at s2 and s3 level. the distal spinal cord shows normal signal intensities.', 0, 1.0), ('right convexity subdural hemorrhage with extension along the right tentorium is similar in appearance to previous exam, currently measuring approximately 14 mm in greatest axial dimension, previously 17 mm. leftward shift of normally midline structures is slightly decreased since previous exam, currently measuring 7 mm, previously 9 mm. mass effect on subjacent cortex is similar. the lateral ventricles are smaller in size bilaterally, likely due to the ventricular shunt. the shunt is unchanged in position. there is unchanged appearance of high- density material within the inferior horns of the bilateral lateral ventricles, likely representing the choroid plexus. left convexity low- density extra- axial fluid collection is also unchanged, measuring 5 mm in greatest axial dimension. again seen are hypodensities of the left caudate head and anterior limb of the internal capsule, which likely represent lacunar infarcts. again noted is partial opacification of the bilateral mastoid air cells.', 1, 0.0), ('there is a small rounded hypodensity in the left thalamus. no other abnormal hypodensities are identified in the brain. there are no intra axial or extra axial masses. there is no hemorrhage, herniation, hydrocephalus or evidence of acute infarction. no osseous abnormalities are identified and the visualized paranasal sinuses are clear.', -1, 0.0), ('air fluid levels and aerosolization of secretions are seen within the frontal sinus, and opacifying the frontal- ethmoid recess. mild mucosal thickening is also seen within the ethmoid air cells. in addition, there are regions of aerosolized secretions within the right side of the ethmoid air cells. air fluid levels and aerosolized secretions are also seen within both partitions of the multiseptate sphenoid sinus, and air fluid levels with mild mucosal thickening are seen within the maxillary sinuses. as described on prior facial ct, there are extensive fractures, including the left zygomatic arch, the lateral wall of the left orbit, the left frontal bone, as well as the left side of the skull base. opacification of the mastoid air cells is also seen on both left and the right. vascular calcifications of the internal carotid arteries are also present. note is made of a prominent left nasal septal spur and septal deviation. in addition, there is an partially erupted left molar tooth.', 0, 1.0), ('there is a small right frontal subdural hematoma without significant mass effect. no intraparenchymal hemorrhage or edema. the ventricles and sulci are normal in caliber and configuration. the basal cisterns are normal. there is soft tissue thickening and hematoma in the left preseptal region. a dense round focus overlying the left preseptal region (2:19) is likely debris on the skin. the globes are intact. few locules of gas and a small extraconal orbital hematoma are seen within right retrobulbar space(2:19), without clear visualization of fracture. there is a nondisplaced fracture of the right occipital condyle (3:6). the paranasal sinuses and mastoid air cells are clear.', 0, 1.0), ('cervical vertebral alignment is maintained. there are end-plate osteophytes and disc bulges at several cervical levels, especially c4-5, c5-6 and c6-7 levels. the degree to which these impinge on the spine canal is unclear, since imaged resolution is suboptimal, but there is suspicion of canal stnosis at c6-7. the cervicomedullary junction appears normal and the foramen magnum is normally wide. in the upper thoracic spine, there is csf seen anterior and posterior to the cord. there is suspicion of canal narrowing at roughly the c7-t1 level.', -1, 0.0), ('there is anterior wedging of c7 vertebral body, of uncertain acuity. no other fractures are identified. prevertebral soft tissue swelling is not well assessed secondary to nasogastric tube and endotracheal tube. degenerative changes are noted throughout the cervical spine with vacuum disc phenomenon and disc space loss at several levels. there is mild grade i retrolisthesis of c4 on c5. ct does not provide intrathecal detail comparable to mr; however, the thecal sac grossly appears intact. again noted are air-fluid levels within the maxillary and sphenoid air spaces, left greater than right.', 1, 0.0), ('the extracalvarial soft tissues are unremarkable. the calvarium and skull base are intact with no underlying fracture. there is a general diffuse ill-defined sclerosis involving the clivus and portions of the skull base. no discrete mass lesion is identified. there is suggestion of underlying coarsening of the trabeculations. there is mucosal thickening of bilateral sphenoid sinuses. no air-fluid levels noted. the mastoid air cells are hypoaerated. there is a scleral band around the left globe. intracranially, the ventricles are mildly prominent but midline. there is subarachnoid hemorrhage over the high left parietal convexity extending to the vertex. a small adjacent subdural hematoma 11 mm in width is identified best on sagittal reformations, series 104b, image 23. there is a mild sulcal effacement in the area of hemorrhage, but otherwise, no significant mass effect results. there is a confluent low attenuation and predominantly a periventricular distribution likely related to chronic microvascular ischemic change. there is no ct evidence of acute cortical stroke.', 1, 0.0), ('there is no evidence of acute hemorrhage, large acute territorial infarction, or overt mass effect. there is no shift of midline structures. ventricles and sulci are normal in size and configuration. there is no evidence of fracture. there is deviation of the nasal septum to the right, (2:3). there is incidental finding of likely osteoma in the right frontal sinus (2:12), measuring 1.4 x 1.1 cm.', 1, 0.0), ('there is patchy restricted diffusion in all lobes of the cerebral cortex . the hippocampi and globus pallidus are spared. a large perivascular space is noted in the left basal ganglia. signal abnormalities in the subcortical and periventricular white matter consistent with chronic small vessel ischemic disease. the ventricles and sulci are normal in size and configuration. there is no hemorrhage, edema, or mass effect. the major intracranial vessel flow voids are preserved. layering fluid in the sphenoid sinuses may be related to recent intubation. the orbits and nasopharyngeal soft tissues are unremarkable. the bony calvaria are normal.', 1, 0.0), ('patient is status post right-sided craniectomy. there is no significant interval change in the appearance of the brain, aside from mild increase in left sided subfalcine herniation, from 8 to 10 mm. there continues to be diffuse cerebral sulcal effacement, with the right lateral ventricle is compressed by the known mass lesion. there is interval decrease in the size of the extradural fluid collection at the site of the craniectomy defect, with lessened quantity of gas in this locale. there is no evidence of new intracranial hemorrhage. there is no new major vascular territorial infarct identified.', -1, 0.0), ('there are small bilateral simple fluid attenuation subdural collections, representing hygromas or chronic subdural hematomas. there is no shift of midline structures. the ventricles, cisterns, maintain a normal configuration, except for a large 4-cm cystic structure in the right infratentorial space that likely represents an arachnoid cyst. periventricular white matter hypodensities are the sequelae of chronic small vessel infarction, and a lacunar infarct is present in the left external capsule. the osseous structures are unremarkable. there is atherosclerotic calcification of the cavernous carotids. there is partial opacification of the ethmoid sinuses and right sphenoid sinus.', -2, 0.0), ('the patient is s/p left frontal craniotomy. a small amount of intracranial gas is seen posterior to the surgical intervention, which could represent postoperative changes. extensive edema is seen in the left frontal lobe at the site of presumed surgery. additionally multiple foci of hemorrhage are seen in the region of the left frontal lobe. midline shift to the right is seen in the frontal region. the ventricles, cisterns, and sulci are unremarkable, without effacement. comparison with prior studies from outside institution would be helpful in further evaluation of these findings.', -2, 1.0), ('from t11 to s4 level, there are no bony abnormalities indicative of metastatic disease. no evidence of epidural mass identified or thecal sac compression seen. mild degenerative disc disease is seen from t11-12 to l5-s1 level with minimal bulging. there is no spinal stenosis or high-grade foraminal narrowing. incidental perineural cysts are visualized at s2 and s3 level. the distal spinal cord shows normal signal intensities.', 0, 1.0), ('there has been no significant change in the appearance of the right frontal-parietal subdural hematoma. the left sided subdural extends more inferiorly into the left temporal region, and its extent in the left frontoparietal region may be slightly larger. no other new areas of hemorrhage are identified. there is no significant change in the effacement of the bifrontal parietal sulci. there is no shift of normally midline structures. again noted is hypoattenuation in the periventricular white matter which is a nonspecific finding but may be consistent with age related involution. the visualized paranasal sinuses and osseous structures are unremarkable.', 1, 0.0), ('since the prior study, there has been development of an approximately 1.7 cm homogeneous mucus retention cyst or polyp in the left maxillary sinus. there has been no change in the right maxillary mucus retention cyst. also unchanged is soft tissue density across the left maxillary sinus drainage pathway. there remains minimal left maxillary mucosal thickening. again demonstrated are changes of endoscopic sinus surgery. the cribriform plates are symmetric. the lamina papyracea are intact. the sphenoid sinus septum inserts on the left carotid groove. the anterior clinoid processes are not pneumatized.', -2, 1.0), ('no disk, vertebral or paraspinal abnormalities seen. there is no sign of a fracture. there is normal alignment of the component vertebrae. the visualized portions of thespinal cord are unremarkable. the thyroid gland is enlarged and heterogenous.', -2, 0.0), ('there is no intraparenchymal or extraaxial hemorrhage. there are no abnormal areas of enhancement. the ventricles, sulci and cisterns are unremarkable. there is no shift of normally midline structures, mass effect or hydrocephalus. in the high right frontal lobe on series 2, image 20 and 21, there appears to be subtle small areas of hypodensity involving the cortex. the density values of the brain parenchyma are otherwise unremarkable. on the most inferior sections, note is made of relatively low positioning of the cerebellar tonsils, possibly caudal ectopia or a chiari 1 malforamtion. the paranasal sinuses are remarkable for opacification of the sphenoid and ethmoid sinuses with bilateral air-fluid levels and mucosal thickening in the maxillary sinuses and frontal sinus. there is also opacification of multiple right mastoid air cells. note is made of an endotracheal tube on the scout image as well, likely accounting for the sinus abnormalities the osseous structures are unremarkable.', -1, 0.0), ('again multiple small foci of subarachnoid blood are seen scattered throughout, primarily the left frontal lobe, and to a lesser extent the right frontal and right temporal lobes. there is no new area of hemorrhage. there is no edema or mass effect. ventricles and sulci are unchanged in size and configuration. the previously described left frontal subgaleal hematoma has extended even further posterolaterally. extensive soft tissue swelling also persists in the left preseptal soft tissues, but
